| *Room* — Emma Donoghue | Jack | From the video — age as the limiting factor |
| *A Catcher in the Rye* — Salinger | Holden Caulfield | Reads as hypocritical teenage ranting — then the ending reveals he was in a mental institution, recontextualising everything |
| *Made You Up* — Francesca Zappia | Alex | Mental illness as the limiting factor |
| *Manic Wars* — Zari Reede | Unnamed | Narrator in a manic/psychotic episode — telling the truth to the best of her ability but perception is skewed |
| *Huck Finn* — Twain | Huck | Young age and social conditioning limit his ability to interpret events objectively |

#### Multiple or unusual structures
| Work | Notes |
|---|---|
| *Pale Fire* — Nabokov | Clues hidden not just in the main text but throughout — the whole story becomes a puzzle. Widely considered one of the best uses of the device. |
| *The Murder of Roger Ackroyd* — Agatha Christie | Famous for its structural use of the device in mystery |
| *The Moonlit Road* — Ambrose Bierce | Short story with three separate unreliable narrators telling the same events |
| *Mistborn* — Brandon Sanderson | Demonstrates that 3rd person unreliable narrator can work |
