## Part 5: Dialogue

*All sections including subtext, iceberg theory, secrets and goals.*

### Good vs bad dialogue

| Bad dialogue | Good dialogue |
|---|---|
| Long-winded | Concise |
| Generic | Specific |
| Surface level | Layers of meaning |
| Disposable | Memorable |

---

### 1. Concise — cut the windbag

Nobody likes a windbag. Long-winded characters work as silly or oblivious supporting roles, rarely as protagonists.

**Exception — the talkative villain:** works only when paired with a hero who has short, terse dialogue. The contrast gives the audience the satisfaction of the hero shutting the villain up.

> *"I am a god, you dull creature."* — paired with a one-line dismissal. The quiet hero vs the monologuing villain.

**Workshop rule:** take any long piece of dialogue and cut it until you can't cut anymore. Less of a bad thing is always a good thing. Removing excess often makes the character seem more insightful — the opposite of what you'd expect.

**Cutting exercise — The Room example:**

Original (bad):
> "She's beautiful. She looks great in a red dress. I think I'm in love with her... I know she doesn't like me because sometimes she's mean to me but sometimes when I'm around her I feel like I want to kiss her and tell her I love her. I don't know, I'm just confused."

Cut version (still not great, but better):
> "She's beautiful. [beat] Sometimes when I'm around her I feel like I want to kiss her."

Everything else was disposable. The red dress, the explanation, the "I don't know, I'm just confused" — all cut. What's left does the same work in a fraction of the words.

---

### 2. Specific — every character has a distinct voice

Great dialogue is specific to the character and their world. If your character speaks exactly the way you speak, they are too generic.

**The cover test:** take any dialogue scene and cover up all the character names. You should still be able to tell who is speaking. If you cannot, the characters sound identical — a major problem.

**The eavesdropping exercise:**

1. Go to a café or public place
2. Record a real conversation (phone, discreetly)
3. Go home and transcribe every word into script format
4. Include: the ums, the cut-offs, the dot-dots, the subject changes, the inappropriate laughter

Real speech is completely different from written dialogue. The transcription will surprise you. This trains your brain to notice the unique speech traits of real people — vocabulary, turns of phrase, how they interrupt each other, how they change subjects — and carry those into your characters.

You do not always need to reinvent the wheel. You need to learn how to spot a good wheel and remember it.

---

### 3. Subtext — what is said between the words

Subtext is the meaning beneath the dialogue — what the speaker really means without saying it directly.

Dialogue that exists only on the literal surface is easy to get bored by. When characters are saying as much between their words as with them, the dialogue becomes engaging.

**Without subtext:**
> "Are you going to go out drinking with boys?"
> "No, god, why don't you trust me?"
> "Because you lie to me and I worry about you."
> "Well you need to get a life, mom."

**With subtext — same meaning, none of it stated directly:**
> "Remember when you used to come home from school and be so excited to tell me all about your day?"
> "When I was like six?"
> "You're still a little girl to me, aren't you?"
> "I'm a girl with places to be."

The real conversation — trust, growing up, letting go — happens entirely between the lines. Neither character says what they actually mean.

→ See also: Part 4 / Prose Craft — Principle 5 covers showing emotion through dialogue; the infodump test covers filtering exposition.

---

### 4. Memorable — unexpected and specific

Memorable lines are unexpected and specific. Being specific has already been covered — the unexpected part is separate.

**The sweet spot:** a line that catches the audience off guard but still feels completely right for the character.

> *"Hasta la vista, baby."*
> *"Here's Johnny."*
> *"I love the smell of napalm in the morning."*
> *"I drink your milkshake."*

**Method:** skip your first instinct for a line. Your first instinct is probably the obvious, expected version. Approach the dialogue from a different angle.

**Warning:** if you cannot think of anything unexpected for a character to say, the problem may be the character — not the dialogue. Any genuinely interesting character has the capacity to surprise the audience. If a character cannot surprise, they may be inherently uninteresting.

Memorable lines are also currency. They are a major reason good actors take on low-budget indie roles.

---

### The iceberg theory (Hemingway)

The dialogue, characters, and plot are just the tip of the iceberg. There is at least 10 times more story beneath the surface — and that is what gives the story its strength. These underlying details are what readers figure out as they read.

If the screenplay has no layers beneath the surface there is no substance to give meaning to the story.

**The goal:** hide the underlying details so the reader puts the pieces together without realising it. Immersion comes from the reader solving the puzzle, not being handed the answer.

> *Pixar's 2+2 rule: don't give them four. Give them two plus two.*

→ See also: Part 4 / Prose Craft — the same 2+2 principle is discussed there in the context of showing vs telling.

---

### Hidden agendas — the real engine of subtext

Dialogue becomes powerful when characters have hidden agendas. The character never says what their true intention is — they beat around the bush.

**Whiplash example:** Fletcher asks Andrew about his parents, his dad's career, his mother leaving. Seems like getting to know a new student. Ten minutes later he uses every detail against Andrew emotionally in front of the class. He never said *I'm gathering ammunition.* The subtext was the hidden agenda the whole time.

**The flat tyre example:** a driver flags someone down for help. They chat warmly about their day and where they are from. What neither reveals is that their friend is hotwiring the car in the background — the conversation is a distraction. Every question now carries hidden weight. Everything seems innocent on the surface but because we know the real motivation, every word means more.

**Rule:** characters never reveal their true intentions. They beat around the bush as much as possible.

---

### The strip-down method

Write what characters actually mean first, then strip it down into the indirect version.

1. Write the scene where characters say exactly what they are thinking
2. Strip it down — replace every direct statement with an indirect one
3. Keep stripping until you can convey the emotion without using the direct words at all
4. If you can, go further — convey it through action instead of words

**Example:**
- Direct: *"I have feelings for you."*
- Indirect: *"Are you still seeing that guy?"*
- Action only: character knocks the girl's lunch off the table when they see her with someone else

**Crazy Stupid Love example:** Emily calls her ex-husband Cal about a broken pilot light on the water heater — except she is visibly sitting in the dining room, not the basement. She is not calling about the water heater. She misses him and needed an excuse to hear his voice. Not one word of that is said in the scene.

**What bad amateur dialogue looks like:**
> *"Hi Cal, I miss you a lot."*
> *"Oh really? I miss you too."*
> *"Too bad I don't want you to know that. Goodbye."*

---

### The contest principle — never name it

The Seinfeld episode *The Contest* is about a competition to see who can go the longest without masturbating. The word is never said once in the entire episode. The audience is given just enough to figure it out.

**Exercise:** write a complete scene about something specific — a divorce, a betrayal, a secret — without ever saying the word that names it. Use context, objects, body language, and indirect dialogue only.

Example (divorce scene — the word "divorce" never appears):
> Anna and Mike glare at each other from opposing seats. Their lawyer mediates. Anna slides a piece of paper over to Mike, never taking her eyes off him. Mike grabs the paper and flips through. A single tear runs down his face. *"Just like that. Twenty years means nothing to you?"* Anna grits her teeth. *"Just sign it if you ever want to see the kids again."*

The reader figures it out. That is the whole point.

---

### Secrets + Goals — the two requirements

Subtext alone is not enough. Characters need two things working together:

| Element | What it does |
|---|---|
| **Secret** | What the character is hiding — gives dialogue its hidden meaning |
| **Goal** | What the character is working toward — gives dialogue its direction |

Without a goal, the character wanders. Without a secret, the dialogue is flat. Together they produce lines that carry weight.

**There is no such thing as small talk in good dialogue.** Every line — including *"how was your day"* — must reflect the character pursuing their goal or protecting their secret. If a line does neither, cut it.

**Applied to examples:**
- *Whiplash:* Fletcher's goal = learn Andrew's weaknesses. Fletcher's secret = he will use them as weapons.
- *Crazy Stupid Love:* Emily's goal = talk to Cal. Emily's secret = she still loves him.

→ See also: Part 3 / Narrative Voice — in an unreliable narrator story, the narrator's secret and goal operate at the level of the entire narration, not just individual scenes.

---

### Quick checklist

- [ ] Can I cut this line by half?
- [ ] Can I tell who is speaking without the character name?
- [ ] Is there a surface conversation and a real conversation happening at the same time?
- [ ] Does this line surprise me — and still feel right for the character?
- [ ] Does every character have at least one quirk in how they speak?

